Part I - (Ford GoBike System Data Exploration and Visualization)¶

by (Uthman Ojodu)¶

Introduction¶

This data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area. The aim of this project is to explore the dataset and ask important questions of the dataset such as which hour of the day has the most bikeshare rides and which age group uses the service most often.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The initial dataset had 183,412 rows and 16 columns which contained information that can be split into three different categories

  • Time : duration of the bike share ride(duration_sec), start time and end time of the bike share rides(start_time,end_time)
  • Station: information about the stations(start_station_id, start_station_name, start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, end_station_id, end_station_name, end_station_latitude, end_station_longitude)

  • User : User information (bike_id,member_gender,member_birth_year,bike_share_for_all_trip).

    After cleaning the dataset, i am left with 174,952 rows and 14 columns of data which can still be split into the above categories.

  • Time :(duration_sec, start_time, end_time, duration_minute, start_hourofday, start_dayofweek, start_dayofmonth)
  • Station: (start_station_name, end_station_name)
  • User : User information (member_gender, member_birth_year, bike_share_for_all_trip, age). ### What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main features of interest involves finding out the average trip duration, and how that relates to the user charcateristics such as the gender, age, user type and if people sharing the trip take longer or lesser trips.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The columns related to the time will show us how longa trip takes and whem the trips are most commomly occuring, and the user columns will help us identify what the main customer groups are and if there are patterns associated with specific groups.

# creating a function for countplots that have the ability for ordering
def countplot(x_axis, order, title, xlabel, ylabel):
    '''
    docstring: function to plt countplots
    input: x_axis, order,title,xlabel,ylabel
    output: plots a countplot with the x_axis plotted against the count of the x_axis, ordered by the order. 
    The plot is titled with the the title, and the x and y axis are labelled wit the xlabel and ylabel respectively.
    '''
    #set background style
    sb.set_style('darkgrid')
    #set figure size
    plt.figure(figsize = [15,5])
    #set countplot bars colors
    color = sb.color_palette('colorblind')[0]
    #plot the chart
    sb.countplot(data = bike, x = x_axis, color = color, order = order)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel);

Question : What is the trip distribution over each day of the month?¶

In [28]:
#getting the order for the days
orderByDay = bike_clean.sort_values(by=['start_dayofmonth'],ascending = True)
orderByDay = orderByDay.groupby('start_dayofmonth').start_dayofmonth.count().index
countplot(bike_clean['start_dayofmonth'],orderByDay,"Frequency of trips by Day",'Days Of Month','Frequency Of Trips')

We can see from the distribution above that the day with the most trips ordered was the last day of the month. The distribution also generally follows a pattern the working days of the week having a higher frequency than the weeekeds. We can further investigate by looking at the distribution of the days in a week

# creating a function for unordered countplots 
def countplots(data, x_axis, title, xlabel, ylabel):
    #set background style
    sb.set_style('darkgrid')
    #set figure size
    plt.figure(figsize = [15,5])
    #set countplot bars colors
    color = sb.color_palette('colorblind')[0]
    #plot the chart
    sb.countplot(data = data, x = x_axis, color = color)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel);

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

For the time related columns , I noticed that the most bike rides occured during the weekdays with a dip on weekends. The most common times during the week which had the most bike rides were the 08:00 and 17:00 hours which conicides wit the time people mostly leave for work and return home from work. Most bike rides lasted mostly beteen 5 and 20 minutes. For the user related columns, I found out most people who use the bike sharing service were males and most of the users fell between the ages of 20 and 40. Most users didn't take up the bike sharing option and preferred to ride alone. Most users were also people who are subscribed to the service as opposed to the casual users.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

There weren't any unsual distributions because i filtered out all the outliers within the age and the duration minute columns to help have a clearer and more representative view of the distribution.

plt.title("Customer Type usage of Bike sharing sevice");

The plot above shows that the subscribers mostly used the service on weekdays with the peak amount of trips coming on Thursdays. There is a decline in the amount of trips for the subscribers heading into the weekend because as we have hypothesised before, the subscribers mostly used the bike sharing service as commutes to and from work.

Conclusions¶

In the exploration, I found that the most bike rides occured during the weekdays with a dip on weekends. The most common times during the week which had the most bike rides were the 08:00 and 17:00 hours which conicides wit the time people mostly leave for work and return home from work. I found that most of the bike rides were between 5 and 20 minutes, most of the members of the service were male, and the most common ages were between 20 and 40. The subscribers outnumber the casual customers, and most of the members of the service did not exercise the bike sharing option often, instead opting to ride alone. Female members tend to have a slightly higher trip durations than the male members, casual users also have higher trip duration times than subscribers. Average trip minutes during the weekdays were almost uniform with an increase during the weekends, members between the age range of 20-40 average higher trip minutes and the trip minutes decrease as the age increases.
